description:
About two hours ago, I called the BPD to report a suspicious bike that had been abandoned with several packages across the street from the federal building where I work and my daughter  goes to school. The bike was in front of the Burger King on Cambridge, near City Hall---and just around the corner from a police station. 
The police just called me back--2 hours later-- to ask if I knew if  the bike and packages were still there. I was told to call 911 back if it was. 

I didn't know that "See Something, Say Something" included "Go Double-Check" on the suspicious package. 

I'm a little shocked that the police didn't check this themselves and that I was called back two hours later and told that if I saw it to call 911 again. 

If citizens are supposed to be vigilant and help keep our city safe, how does this example make us feel like our calls and concerns matter?

Thank you for reviewing this.
